Yes, that works.  At least, it generates a DTD that the dataset will validate against, although that DTD only represents the subset of the database that was included in the dataset \(so won't necessarily work with other datasets from the same database\).

However, I've since discovered that the other option I was suggesting \("\(A|B|C\)\*"\) is already available - it's the CHOICE content model from bug \#884422.  I had to reference the DTD writer directly i.e.

FlatDtdWriter dtdWriter = new FlatDtdWriter\(new FileWriter\("database.dtd"\)\);
dtdWriter.setContentModel\(FlatDtdWriter.CHOICE\);
dtdWriter.write\(connection.createDataSet\(\)\);

instead of

FlatDtdDataSet.write\(connection.createDataSet\(\), new FileOutputStream\("database.dtd"\)\);

but that does what I need.  To be honest, I was a little surprised this wasn't made the default FlatDtdDataSet behaviour when it was added.

As for updating the FAQs, I'll have a think about how it/they might be changed, such that they would have been more help.

tickets.description:
Following the sample code on http://www.dbunit.org/faq.html\#generatedtd I generated a DTD for my database.

FlatDtdDataSet.write\(connection.createDataSet\(\), new FileOutputStream\("inv\_fundcentre.dtd"\)\);

Then, following the depDataset sample code in http://www.dbunit.org/faq.html\#extract I generated an XML dataset for a table and its dependencies.

String\[\] depTableNames = TablesDependencyHelper.getAllDependentTables\(connection, new String\[\] \{"FUND\_DOCUMENTS", "FUND\_TYPE\_DOCUMENTS"\}\);
IDataSet depDataSet = connection.createDataSet\(depTableNames\);
FlatXmlDataSet.write\(depDataSet, new FileOutputStream\("dependents.xml"\)\);

However, the generated XML is not valid according to the DTD as the tables do not appear in the order specified in the dataset \!ELEMENT.
Either the DTD should sort the subelements into the same order, or \(probably easier\) instead of

&lt;\!ELEMENT dataset \(
A\*,
B\*,
C\*\)&gt;

it could use

&lt;\!ELEMENT dataset \(\(
A |
B |
C\)\*\)&gt;

the current assertEquals\(\) method is
not flexible enough, as there is no way to extend it \(it's a static
method\) if you want to change the way the comparison is done \(in my
current project, for instance, we need to ignore rows marked as
"\[IGNORE\]", and the solution was to copy-and-paste that method on our
own class, which is not good\). So, I would suggest that we refactor
this method by creating an overloaded version that receive some sort
of DatasetComparator \(or TableComparator\) parameter as well, then
users that need custom comparison call this method.

Or, better yet, we should improve the way the static methods are
handled in the whole Assertion class. Instead of :

public class Assertion \{

static void assertEquals\( ..., ... \) \{
// do it
\}
\}

We should have:

public class Assertion \{

private static final Assertion INSTANCE = new Assertion\(\);

protected void compare\( ..., ... \) \{
// do it as well, but break steps in calls to
// protected methods that could be overridden
\}

static void assertEquals\( ..., ... \) \{
INSTANCE.compara\( ..., ....\);
\}
\}

Than if I want to customize Assertion, I create my own
CustomAssertion, customize to proper methods, and static import that
class \(instead of Assertion\) on my test cases.

public class MyCustomAssertion extends Assertion \{

private static final MyCustomAssertion MY\_INSTANCE = new MyCustomAssertion\(\);

protected void compareStepX\( ..., ... \) \{
// my sub-class does not need to redefine the whole compare\(\) method, just
// some steps
\}

static void assertEquals\( ..., ... \) \{
MY\_INSTANCE.compara\( ..., ....\);
\}
\}

That would be a clearer approach in my opinion, as it kind of
implements the Template Method pattern.

