tickets.description:
DBUnit currently has several logging statements for tracing the execution of the program \(entry into and exit out of various methods\), e.g.

public void addRow\(\) throws DataSetException
\{
logger.debug\("addRow\(\) - start"\);

int columnCount = \_metaData.getColumns\(\).length;
\_rowList.add\(new Object\[columnCount\]\);
\}

Since these all log at the DEBUG level, it makes for very verbose logs.  This kind of thing ought to be logged at TRACE, instead.

SLF4J has a nice feature that would be ideal for use in situations like this, known as "ExtendedLogging" \(http://www.slf4j.org/extensions.html\#extended\_logger\).  Basically, instead of writing "log.debug\("....."\), you'd write "log.entry\(\)", optionally passing in the same parameters that are being passed into the method you're tracing.  Similarly, you can do "log.exit\(\)" before returning from the method \(optionally passing in the return value as well\) to log exiting from the method.  There are similar methods for catching and throwing exceptions, as well.

The entry and exit methods log at the TRACE level \(others log at ERROR, appropriately\).  Even nicer, the logging statements also have specific Markers attached to them which can be used by Marker-aware SLF4J implementations \(e.g. logback\) to further filter these messages if the user is not interested in seeing execution tracing \(or is only interested in seeing a portion of that tracing, such as only method entry information\).

Switching to this setup for logging these kinds of messages would:
1\. Make DEBUG logs less verbose
2\. Ease maintenance, since logging messages automatically contain the name of the method being traced; developers won't have to keep that String in sync with the method name.
3\. Enhance usability by allowing the end user to easily fine-tune logging output to see exactly what information they're interested in.

